CLI Solution
Create the Storage Account:
You can create the storage account using the following Azure CLI command:
az storage account create \
  --name xfusionst13095 \
  --resource-group <your-resource-group> \
  --location eastus \
  --sku Standard_LRS \
  --kind StorageV2 \
  --access-tier Hot

Explanation:
--name: The name of the storage account (xfusionst13095).
--resource-group: Replace <your-resource-group> with the name of your resource group.
--location: Choose the region (e.g., eastus).
--sku: Specifies the performance and replication type (Standard_LRS for locally redundant storage).
--kind: The storage account type (StorageV2 for general-purpose v2).
--access-tier: The access tier for the blob data (Hot for frequently accessed data).

Create the Private Blob Container:
After creating the storage account, you can create the private blob container xfusion-blob-16521 using the following command:
az storage container create \
  --name xfusion-blob-16521 \
  --account-name xfusionst13095 \
  --public-access off

Explanation:
--name: The name of the blob container (xfusion-blob-16521).
--account-name: The name of the storage account (xfusionst13095).
--public-access off: This ensures the blob container is private (no public access).

Azure Portal Solution
Go to the Azure Portal: Open Azure Portal.
Create the Storage Account:
In the left-hand navigation pane, search for "Storage accounts" and select it.
Click "+ Create" to create a new storage account.
In the Basics tab:
Subscription: Choose your subscription.
Resource Group: Select the existing resource group.
Storage Account Name: Enter xfusionst13095 as the storage account name.
Region: Choose East US (or your preferred region).
Performance: Choose Standard for general-purpose.
Replication: Select Locally redundant storage (LRS).
Access Tier: Choose Hot for frequently accessed data.
After entering the required details, click Review + Create and then click Create.
Create the Private Blob Container:
After the storage account is created, navigate to it.
Under the Blob service section, click on Containers.
Click + Container to create a new container.
In the Name field, enter xfusion-blob-16521.
Under Public access level, select Private (no anonymous access).
Click Create to create the container.
Verifying the Creation
To verify the storage account and blob container:
CLI: List the containers in the storage account:
az storage container list --account-name xfusionst13095 --query "[].name" --output table
This should show the xfusion-blob-16521 container.
Portal: Navigate to the Storage Account > Containers to see the list of containers. You should see xfusion-blob-16521 listed there.
